widgets_values:
This trick pads the video with 4 copies of the initial frame, allowing you to set a higher noise augmentation for the first frame, giving you a better generated result at the cost of slightly lower coherence to the initial image. If you enable these nodes, also enable the group that trims the first 4 garbage frames after the video is decoded. 

The trick works because of the way the model was trained and because the VAE compresses 4 pixel frames into one latent frame. It's experimental so you'll have to test for yourself.

More source cfg = larger change from input video

More target cfg = more prompt adherence to the target

Change skip and drift steps before cfg

nodes.title: Source Prompt
widgets_values: A model wearing a black bra and panties is covered heavily with tattoos. The model has long black hair and dark eyes. She is wearing a black wristband. She runs her hand over her body and looks at the camera.

Skip steps: Basically just your standard denoise settings 
(1 - (4 skip steps/20 steps) = .8 denoise) 
higher skip steps, closer to source video, because denoise is lower

Middle steps: Add random noise, but also help maintain coherence 
(20 steps - 4 skip steps - 8 drift steps = 8 middle steps)
Less influence on the amount of change than drift/skip, but essential for maintaining cohesion of source while applying 

Drift steps Model runs as normal without influence from source image/video.
